Syncs a scaffolded project's CTX tooling files to match the upstream CTX repository: install-tools.sh itself, the ctx-* binaries it builds, and a fixed set of tooling files (linters, check scripts, runtime prompts, Claude settings) that install-tools.sh doesn't touch. This is the single command a project runs to catch up to upstream doctrine and tool changes after scaffolding.

The script takes the CTX repo path as `$1` or `CTX_REPO` env var, defaulting to `../CTX`. It unconditionally overwrites every synced file on each run with no version checking or local-modification detection, matching install-tools.sh's precedent. CTX_REPO validity is delegated to install-tools.sh itself — if the path is bad, install-tools.sh fails fast rather than having two error paths.

Runtime prompt files (summarizer-leaf.md, summarizer-rollup.md, briefer-*.md) live in `prompts/` and are loaded at runtime by ctx-scan, ctx-summarize, and ctx-brief — these are resolved against the project root, not the tooling repo. The CLAUDE.md sync is surgical: it extracts only the marked `<!-- BEGIN/END GENERATED tool-contracts -->` block from the upstream template and splices it into the local CLAUDE.md, preserving project-specific prose outside the markers. Both source and target files must have the markers present or the sync fails.

The script runs install-tools.sh partway through (after syncing install-tools.sh itself to ensure the latest version runs), then completes remaining syncs, and finally overwrites itself last — this ordering ensures Bash finishes reading the running script before the file is replaced.